# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: consent-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:consent-management/consent] United Nations agencies and initiatives in sex education programs believe that teaching the topic of consent as part of comprehensive sexuality education is beneficial.
[src:consent-management/consent] Types of consent include implied consent, express consent, informed consent, and unanimous consent.
[src:consent-management/consent] The concept of end-user given consent plays an important role in digital regulations such as the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:consent-management/consent] The GDPR (Article 6) defines a set of different legal bases for the lawful processing of personal data.
[src:consent-management/consent] End-users' consent is only one of these possible bases.
[src:consent-management/consent] However, because of the GDPR enforcement (in 2018) and other legal obligations, data controllers (online service providers) have widely developed consent-obtaining mechanisms in recent years.
[src:consent-management/consent] According to the GDPR, end-users' consent should be *valid*, *freely given*, *specific*, *informed*, and *active*.
[src:consent-management/consent] But the lack of enforceability regarding obtaining lawful consent has been a challenge in the digital world.
[src:consent-management/consent] As an example, a 2020 study, showed that the Big Tech, i.e.
[src:consent-management/consent] Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple, and Microsoft (GAFAM), use dark patterns in their consent obtaining mechanisms, which raises doubts regarding the lawfulness of the obtained consent.
[src:consent-management/consent] For example, participation in a contact sport usually implies consent to contact with other participants, implicitly agreed and often defined by the rules of the sport.
[src:consent-management/consent] Another specific example is where a boxer cannot complain of being punched on the nose by an opponent; implied consent will be valid where the violence is **ordinarily and reasonably to be contemplated as incidental to the sport in question**.
[src:consent-management/consent] Express consent exists when there is oral or written agreement, particularly in a contract.
[src:consent-management/consent] For example, businesses may require that persons sign a waiver (called a liability waiver) acknowledging and accepting the hazards of an activity.
[src:consent-management/consent] This proves express consent and prevents the person from filing a tort lawsuit for unauthorised actions.
[src:consent-management/consent] In English law, the principle of *volenti non fit injuria* (Latin: "to a willing person, injury is not done") applies not only to participants in sport but also to spectators and to any others who willingly engage in activities where there is a risk of injury.
[src:consent-management/consent] Consent has also been used as a defense in cases involving accidental deaths during sex, which occur during sexual bondage.
[src:consent-management/consent] *Time* (May 23, 1988) referred to this latter example as the "*rough-sex defense*".
[src:consent-management/consent] It is not effective in English law in cases of serious injury or death.
[src:consent-management/consent] As a term of jurisprudence, prior provision of consent signifies a possible defence (an excuse or justification) against civil or criminal liability.
[src:consent-management/consent] Defendants who use this defense argue that they should not be held liable for a tort or a crime, since the actions in question took place with the plaintiff or "victim's" prior consent and permission.
[src:consent-management/consent] In medical law, consent is important to protect a medical practitioner from liability for harm to a patient arising from a procedure.
[src:consent-management/consent] There are exemptions, such as when the patient cannot give consent.
[src:consent-management/consent] Also, a medical practitioner must explain the significant risks of a procedure or medication (those that might change the patient's mind about whether to proceed with the treatment) before the patient can give binding consent.
[src:consent-management/consent] This was explored in Australia in *Rogers v Whitaker*.
[src:consent-management/consent] If a practitioner does not explain a material risk that subsequently eventuates, then that is considered negligent.
[src:consent-management/consent] These material risks include the loss of a chance of a better result if a more experienced surgeon had performed the procedure.
[src:consent-management/consent] This change reflects the Guidance of the General Medical Council on the requirement to consent to patients and removes the rule of medical paternalism.
[src:consent-management/consent] Social scientists are generally required to obtain informed consent from research participants before asking interview questions or conducting an experiment.
[src:consent-management/consent] Informed consent in this context generally means explaining the study's purpose to research participants and obtaining a signed or verbal affirmation that the study participants understand the procedures to be used and consent to take part in the study.
[src:consent-management/consent] Some types of social scientific research, such as psychological experiments, may use deception as part of the study; in these cases, researchers may not fully describe the procedures to participants, and thus participants are not fully informed.
[src:consent-management/consent] However, researchers are required to debrief participants immediately after the experiment is concluded.
[src:consent-management/consent] Certain populations are considered vulnerable, and besides informed consent, special protections must be made available to them.
[src:consent-management/consent] These include persons who are incarcerated, pregnant women, persons with disabilities, and persons who have a mental disability.
[src:consent-management/consent] Children are considered unable to provide informed consent.
[src:consent-management/consent] Some countries, such as New Zealand with its Resource Management Act and its Building Act, use the term "consent" for the legal process that provides planning permission for developments like subdivisions, bridges or buildings.
[src:consent-management/consent] Achieving permission results in getting "Resource consent" or "Building consent".
[src:consent-management/consent] In Canada, "consent means [...] the voluntary agreement of the complainant to engage in sexual activity" without abuse or exploitation of "trust, power or authority", coercion or threats.
[src:consent-management/consent] Consent can also be revoked at any moment.
[src:consent-management/consent] The Supreme Court of British Columbia ruled that badgering alone, followed by an agreement, does not meet the threshold of coercion to vitiate consent.
[src:consent-management/consent] Sexual consent plays an important role in defining what sexual assault is, since sexual activity without consent by all parties is rape.
[src:consent-management/consent] In the late 1980s, academic Lois Pineau argued we must move towards a more communicative model of sexuality so that consent becomes more explicit and clear, objective and layered, with a more comprehensive model than "no means no" or "yes means yes".
[src:consent-management/consent] Many universities have instituted campaigns about consent.
[src:consent-management/consent] Creative campaigns with attention-grabbing slogans and images that market consent can be effective tools to raise awareness of campus sexual assault and related issues.
[src:consent-management/consent] Since the late 1990s, new models of sexual consent have been proposed.
[src:consent-management/consent] Minors below a certain age, the age of sexual consent in that jurisdiction, are deemed not able to give valid consent by law to sexual acts.
[src:consent-management/consent] Likewise, persons with Alzheimer's disease or similar disabilities may be unable to give legal consent to sexual relations, even with their spouse.
[src:consent-management/consent] Within literature, definitions surrounding consent and how it should be communicated have been contradictory, limited, or without consensus.
[src:consent-management/consent] Roffee argued that legal definitions need to be universal to avoid confusion in legal decisions.
[src:consent-management/consent] He also demonstrated how the moral notion of consent does not always align with the legal concept.
[src:consent-management/consent] For example, some adult siblings or other family members may voluntarily enter a relationship; however, the legal system still deems this as incestual, and therefore a crime.
[src:consent-management/consent] Roffee argues that the use of particular language in the legislation regarding these familial sexual activities manipulates the reader to view it as immoral and criminal, even if all parties are consenting.
[src:consent-management/consent] Similarly, some children under the legal age of consent may knowingly and willingly choose to be in a sexual relationship.
[src:consent-management/consent] However, the law does not view this as legitimate.
[src:consent-management/consent] Whilst there is a necessity for an age of consent, it does not allow for varying levels of awareness and maturity.
[src:consent-management/consent] Here it can be seen how a moral and a legal understanding do not always align.
[src:consent-management/consent] Initiatives in sex education programs are working towards including and foregrounding topics of and discussions of sexual consent in primary, high school, and college Sex Ed curricula.
[src:consent-management/consent] In the UK, the Personal Social Health and Economic Education Association (PSHEA) is working to produce and introduce Sex Ed lesson plans in British schools that include lessons on "consensual sexual relationships," "the meaning and importance of consent" as well as "rape myths".
[src:consent-management/consent] In U.S., California-Berkeley University has implemented affirmative and continual consent in education and in the school's policies.
[src:consent-management/consent] In Canada, the Ontario government has introduced a revised Sex Ed curriculum to Toronto schools, including new discussions of sex and affirmative consent, healthy relationships and communication.
[src:consent-management/consent] Affirmative consent (enthusiastic yes) is when both parties agree to sexual conduct, either through clear verbal communication or nonverbal cues or gestures.
[src:consent-management/consent] It involves communication and the active participation of the people involved.
[src:consent-management/consent] By definition, affirmative consent cannot be given if a person is intoxicated, unconscious, or asleep.
[src:consent-management/consent] To obtain affirmative consent, rather than waiting to say or for a partner to say "no", one gives and seeks an explicit "yes".
[src:consent-management/consent] This can come as a smile, a nod, or a verbal yes, as long as it is unambiguous, enthusiastic, and ongoing.
[src:consent-management/consent] "There's varying language, but the language gets to the core of people having to communicate their affirmation to participate in sexual behavior," said Denice Labertew of the California Coalition Against Sexual Assault.
[src:consent-management/consent] "It requires a fundamental shift in how we think about sexual assault.
[src:consent-management/consent] The above concept of affirmative consent has become more mainstream and promoted in public discourse, institutions, and the workplace, especially following the #MeToo scandals.
[src:consent-management/consent] However, feminists from varying political backgrounds have voiced concerns and critiques of affirmative consent as a solution to both sexual assault and creating sexual equality and autonomy between all genders.
[src:consent-management/consent] If women, queer people, and other marginalized groups are not free to say no, why would they be free to say yes?
[src:consent-management/consent] Feminists have been seeking for more transformative alternatives that go beyond a (verbal) agreement between sexual partners, examining the issue as a political question related to power structures, the influence of neoliberal perceptions of the self and the complexity of human desire.
[src:consent-management/consent] The common form of affirmative consent assumes that humans act as rational and independent beings who, at any point in any interaction, are fully aware of what they are (not) consenting to, whether they want to and can make a conscious, valid decision.
[src:consent-management/consent] Consent, as it is practiced now, thus requires us to rationalize desires and prioritize thinking over feeling, and reason over emotions.
[src:consent-management/consent] The resulting consent is shaped in a neoliberal form of contractualism, which makes a withdrawal of consent or a change in the conditions of the activity at stake rather challenging.
[src:consent-management/consent] This form of consent, as a contract, assumes consent to happen between two (or more) individuals and rational actors, and it does not give room to forms of discomfort, vulnerability, or discussion within the practice consented to.
[src:consent-management/consent] This contractualism mostly relies on verbal, affirmative consent and overlooks non-verbal or alternative ways of consenting.
[src:consent-management/consent] The latter is rather essentializing signs of affirmation and, due to its reliance on verbal consent in form of understandable words, can be ableist by invalidating non-verbal consent.
[src:consent-management/consent] Furthermore, contractualism assumes consent to be rational by nature and implies that we always know rationally whether we want to consent to something.
[src:consent-management/consent] However, especially in the sphere of interpersonal sexual and non-sexual activities, our own needs or desires are not always rational but can rather be ambiguous, contradicting or unclear.
[src:consent-management/consent] Consent as neoliberal contractualism cannot include and reflect this ambiguity and the lack of rationality.
[src:consent-management/consent] Arguably, there is a distinction that is rarely made in the debate around consent: the socio-cultural and the legal.
[src:consent-management/consent] While talking about consent, arguments are often informed and talked about within a legal framework: What do we need to be protected in the current legal framework?
[src:consent-management/consent] Which formulations give the best protection to victims of sexual violence?
[src:consent-management/consent] However, when talking about this protection, there is also a need for protection through prevention, a protection by society rather than the law.
[src:consent-management/consent] While it is not necessarily a given that affirmative consent provides the best legal protection for victims without taking away their agency, there is another danger in linking the legal debate and our overall understanding of consent.
[src:consent-management/consent] A socio-cultural debate would be one around our needs, attitudes, and behaviors and the changes needed, which arguably is a more complex debate to hold and handle.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The Do Not Track header was originally proposed in 2009 and was adopted by most major browsers within a few years.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] However, the header failed to find widespread respect among publishers, due to the lack of legislation requiring companies to support the DNT header and confusion about the header's meaning.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The DNT header was abandoned by standards bodies such as the W3C.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] As of 2025, some browsers had removed the header, including Apple Safari and Mozilla Firefox.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Following the failure of the DNT initiative, a coalition of US-based internet companies announced the creation of the Global Privacy Control header which is intended to have explicit legal force under privacy legislation.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The DNT header accepts three values: `1` in case the user does not want to be tracked *(opt-out)*, `00` in case the user consents to be tracked *(opt-in)*, or *null* (no header sent) if the user has not expressed a preference.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The default behavior required by the document draft is not to send the header unless the user enables the setting via their browser or their choice is implied by the use of that specific browser.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Alternative permitted values are `0` if the user prefers to permit tracking, and `null` if the user has not expressed a preference.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The user's DNT preference can also be read from the JavaScript `navigator.doNotTrack` property which returns one of the values `1`, `0` or `null`.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In 2007, several consumer advocacy groups asked the U.S.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Federal Trade Commission (FTC) to create a Do Not Track list for online advertising.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The proposal would have required that online advertisers submit their information to the FTC, which would compile a machine-readable list of the domain names used by those companies to place cookies or otherwise track consumers.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In July 2009, researchers Christopher Soghoian and Sid Stamm implemented support for the Do Not Track header in the Firefox web browser via a prototype add-on.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Stamm was, at the time, a privacy engineer at Mozilla, while Soghoian soon afterward started working at the FTC.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Senate privacy hearing, FTC Chairman Jon Leibowitz told the Senate Commerce Committee that the commission was exploring the idea of proposing a "do-not-track" list.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In December 2010, the FTC issued a privacy report that called for a "do-not-track" system that would enable people to avoid having their actions being monitored online.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] One week later, Microsoft announced that its next browser would include support for Tracking Protection Lists that block tracking of consumers using blacklists supplied by third parties.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In January 2011, Mozilla announced that its Firefox browser would soon provide a Do Not Track solution, via a browser header.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Microsoft's Internet Explorer 9, Apple's Safari, Opera and Google Chrome all later added support for the header approach.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In August 2015, a coalition of privacy groups led by the Electronic Frontier Foundation using W3C's Tracking Preference Expression (DNT) standard proposed that "Do not track" be the goal for advocates to demand of businesses.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In January 2019, the W3C Tracking Protection Working Group was disbanded, citing "insufficient deployment of these extensions" and lack of "indications of planned support among user agents, third parties, and the ecosystem at large".
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Beginning the following month, Apple removed DNT support from Safari starting from version 12.1, citing that it could be used as a "fingerprinting variable" for tracking.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In December 2024, developer builds of Firefox lost support for the DNT header.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Mozilla updated documentation about DNT to clarify that the browser no longer supports the header and recommended to use Global Privacy Control header instead.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] On February 4, 2025, Firefox 135.0 removed support for the DNT header for all users.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] When using the "Express" settings upon installation, a Do Not Track option is enabled by default for Internet Explorer 10 and Windows 8.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Microsoft faced criticism for its decision to enable Do Not Track by default from advertising companies, who say that use of the Do Not Track header should be a choice made by the user and must not be automatically enabled.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The companies also said that this decision would violate the Digital Advertising Alliance's agreement with the U.S. government to honor a Do Not Track system, because the coalition said it would only honor such a system if it were not enabled by default by web browsers.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] A Microsoft spokesperson defended its decision however, stating that users would prefer a web browser that automatically respected their privacy.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] On September 7, 2012, Roy Fielding, an author of the Do Not Track proposal, committed a patch to the source code of the Apache HTTP Server, which would make the server explicitly ignore any use of the Do Not Track header by users of Internet Explorer 10.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Fielding wrote that Microsoft's decision "deliberately violates" the Do Not Track specification because it "does not protect anyone's privacy unless the recipients believe it was set by a real human being, with a real preference for privacy over personalization".
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The Do Not Track specification did not explicitly mandate that the use of Do Not Track actually be a choice until after the feature was implemented in Internet Explorer 10.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] According to Fielding, Microsoft knew its Do Not Track signals would be ignored, and that its goal was to effectively give an illusion of privacy while still catering to their own interests.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] On October 9, 2012, Fielding's patch was commented out, restoring the previous behavior.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Very few advertising companies actually supported DNT, due to a lack of regulatory or voluntary requirements for its use and unclear standards over how websites should respond to the header.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Websites that honor DNT requests include Medium and Pinterest.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Despite offering the option in its Chrome web browser, Google did not implement support for DNT on its websites, and directed users to its online privacy settings and opt-outs for interest-based advertising instead.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The Digital Advertising Alliance, Council of Better Business Bureaus and the Data & Marketing Association does not require its members to honor DNT signals.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Usage of ad blocking software to block web trackers and advertising has become increasingly common, with users citing both privacy concerns and performance impact as justification for its use.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Apple and Mozilla have begun to add privacy enhancements, such as "tracking protection", to their browsers, designed to reduce undue cross-site tracking.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In addition, laws such as the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) have imposed restrictions on how companies are to store and process personal information.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] Princeton University associate professor of computer science Jonathan Mayer, who was a member of the W3C's working group for DNT, argued that the concept is a "failed experiment".
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In 2020, a coalition of US-based internet companies announced the Global Privacy Control header that intended to replace the DNT header.
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] The creators hope that this new header will meet the definition of "user-enabled global privacy controls" defined by the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) and the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:consent-management/do-not-track] In this case, the new header would be automatically strengthened by existing laws and companies would be required to honor it.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The **General Data Protection Regulation** (Regulation (EU) 2016/679), abbreviated **GDPR**, is a European Union regulation on information privacy in the European Union (EU) and the European Economic Area (EEA).
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR is an important component of EU privacy law and human rights law, in particular Article 8(1) of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It also governs the transfer of personal data outside the EU and EEA.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR's goals are to enhance individuals' control and rights over their personal information and to simplify the regulations for international business.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It supersedes the Data Protection Directive 95/46/EC and, among other things, simplifies the terminology.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The European Parliament and Council of the European Union adopted the GDPR on 14 April 2016, to become effective on 25 May 2018.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As an EU regulation (instead of a directive), the GDPR has direct legal effect and does not require transposition into national law.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] However, it also provides flexibility for individual member states to modify (derogate from) some of its provisions.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As an example of the Brussels effect, the regulation became a model for many other laws around the world, including in Brazil, Japan, Singapore, South Africa, South Korea, Sri Lanka, and Thailand.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] After leaving the European Union, the United Kingdom enacted its "UK GDPR", identical to the GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), adopted on 28 June 2018, has many similarities with the GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR also contains 173 recitals purposed to clarify scope and rationale for the regulatory provisions, as well as its legislative intents – Recital 4, for instance, begins by saying that the processing of personal data should be "designed to serve mankind".
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation applies if the data controller, or processor, or the data subject (person) is based in the EU.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation also applies to organisations based outside the EU if they collect or process personal data of individuals located inside the EU.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation does not apply to the processing of data by private persons provided that the purpose has no connection to a professional or commercial activity." (Recital 18).
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] According to the European Commission, "Personal data is information that relates to an identified or identifiable individual.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If you cannot directly identify an individual from that information, then you need to consider whether the individual is still identifiable.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The data protection reform package also includes a separate Data Protection Directive for the police and criminal justice sector that provides rules on personal data exchanges at State level, Union level, and international levels.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A single set of rules applies to all EU member states.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Each member state establishes an independent supervisory authority (SA) to hear and investigate complaints, sanction administrative offences, etc.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] SAs in each member state co-operate with other SAs, providing mutual assistance and organising joint operations.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If a business has multiple establishments in the EU, it must have a single SA as its "lead authority", based on the location of its "main establishment" where the main processing activities take place.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The lead authority thus acts as a "one-stop shop" to supervise all the processing activities of that business throughout the EU.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A European Data Protection Board (EDPB) co-ordinates the SAs.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] EDPB thus replaces the **Article 29** Data Protection Working Party.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are exceptions for data processed in an employment context or in national security that still might be subject to individual country regulations.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If informed *consent* is used as the lawful basis for processing, consent must have been explicit for data collected and each purpose data is used for.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consent must be a specific, freely given, plainly worded, and unambiguous affirmation given by the data subject; an online form which has consent options structured as an opt-out selected by default is a violation of the GDPR, as the consent is not unambiguously affirmed by the user.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In addition, multiple types of processing may not be "bundled" together into a single affirmation prompt, as this is not specific to each use of data, and the individual permissions are not freely given.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data subjects must be allowed to withdraw this consent at any time, and the process of doing so must not be harder than it was to opt in.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A data controller may not refuse service to users who decline consent to processing that is not strictly necessary in order to use the service.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consent for children, defined in the regulation as being less than 16 years old (although with the option for member states to individually make it as low as 13 years old), must be given by the child's parent or custodian, and verifiable.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If consent to processing was already provided under the Data Protection Directive, a data controller does not have to re-obtain consent if the processing is documented and obtained in compliance with the GDPR's requirements (Recital 171).
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The right of access (**Article 15**) is a data subject right.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It gives people the right to access their personal data and information about how this personal data is being processed.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A data subject must be able to transfer personal data from one electronic processing system to and into another, without being prevented from doing so by the data controller.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data that has been sufficiently anonymised is excluded, but data that has been only de-identified but remains possible to link to the individual in question, such as by providing the relevant identifier, is not.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Both data being 'provided' by the data subject and data being 'observed', such as about behaviour, are included.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In addition, the data must be provided by the controller in a structured and commonly used standard electronic format.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The right to data portability is provided by **Article 20**.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A *right to be forgotten* was replaced by a more limited *right of erasure* in the version of the GDPR that was adopted by the European Parliament in March 2014.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are some instances where this objection does not apply.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A task being carried out for public interest.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] GDPR is also clear that the data controller must inform individuals of their right to object from the first communication the controller has with them.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This should be clear and separate from any other information the controller is providing and give them their options for how best to object to the processing of their data.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are instances the controller can refuse a request, in the circumstances that the objection request is "manifestly unfounded" or "excessive", so each case of objection must be looked at individually.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Other countries such as Canada are also, following the GDPR, considering legislation to regulate automated decision making under privacy laws, even though there are policy questions as to whether this is the best way to regulate AI.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In the judgment *Österreichische Post* (C-300/21) the Court of Justice of the European Union gave an interpretation of the right to compensation.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Article 82(1) GDPR requires for the award of damages *(i)* an infringement of the GDPR, *(ii)* (actual) damage suffered and *(iii)* a causal link between the infringement and the damage suffered.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is not necessary that the damage suffered reaches a certain degree of seriousness.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There is no European defined concept of damage.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Compensation is determined nationally in accordance with national law.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data processors are only liable for damage caused by processing in breach of obligations specifically imposed on processors by the GDPR, or for damage caused by processing which is outside, or contrary to, the lawful instructions of the data controller.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must clearly disclose any data collection, declare the lawful basis and purpose for data processing, and state how long data is being retained and if it is being shared with any third parties or outside of the EEA.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Firms have the obligation to protect data of employees and consumers to the degree where only the necessary data is extracted with minimum interference with data privacy from employees, consumers, or third parties.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Firms should have internal controls and regulations for various departments such as audit, internal controls, and operations.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data subjects have the right to request a portable copy of the data collected by a controller in a common format, as well as the right to have their data erased under certain circumstances.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Public authorities, and businesses whose core activities consist of regular or systematic processing of personal data, are required to employ a *data protection officer* (DPO), who is responsible for managing compliance with the GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must report data breaches to national supervisory authorities within 72 hours if they have an adverse effect on user privacy.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In some cases, violators of the GDPR may be fined up to €20 million or up to 4% of the annual worldwide turnover of the preceding financial year in case of an enterprise, whichever is greater.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] To be able to demonstrate compliance with the GDPR, the data controller must implement measures that meet the principles of data protection by design and by default.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] **Article 25** requires data protection measures to be designed into the development of business processes for products and services.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Such measures include pseudonymising personal data, by the controller, as soon as possible (Recital 78).
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is the responsibility and the liability of the data controller to implement effective measures and be able to demonstrate the compliance of processing activities even if the processing is carried out by a data processor on behalf of the controller (Recital 74).
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As such, the data subject must also be provided with contact details for the data controller and their designated data protection officer, where applicable.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data protection impact assessments (**Article 35**) have to be conducted when specific risks occur to the rights and freedoms of data subjects.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Risk assessment and mitigation is required and prior approval of the data protection authorities is required for high risks.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A report by the European Union Agency for Network and Information Security elaborates on what needs to be done to achieve privacy and data protection by default.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It specifies that encryption and decryption operations must be carried out locally, not by remote service, because both keys and data must remain in the power of the data owner if any privacy is to be achieved.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The report specifies that outsourced data storage on remote clouds is practical and relatively safe if only the data owner, not the cloud service, holds the decryption keys.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] An example is encryption, which renders the original data unintelligible in a process that cannot be reversed without access to the correct decryption key.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR requires for the additional information (such as the decryption key) to be kept separately from the pseudonymised data.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Another example of pseudonymisation is tokenisation, which is a non-mathematical approach to protecting data at rest that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes, referred to as tokens.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] While the tokens have no extrinsic or exploitable meaning or value, they allow for specific data to be fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Tokenisation does not alter the type or length of data, which means it can be processed by legacy systems such as databases that may be sensitive to data length and type.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This also requires much fewer computational resources to process and less storage space in databases than traditionally encrypted data.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Pseudonymisation is a privacy-enhancing technology and is recommended to reduce the risks to the concerned data subjects and also to help controllers and processors to meet their data protection obligations (Recital 28).
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Such requirements may be modified by each EU country.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The records shall be in electronic form and the controller or the processor and, where applicable, the controller's or the processor's representative, shall make the record available to the supervisory authority on request.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Controllers and processors of personal data must put in place *appropriate technical and organizational measures* to implement the data protection principles.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Business processes that handle personal data must be designed and built with consideration of the principles and provide safeguards to protect data (for example, using pseudonymization or full anonymization where appropriate).
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must design information systems with privacy in mind.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] For instance, using the highest-possible privacy settings by default, so that the datasets are not publicly available by default and cannot be used to identify a subject.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] No personal data may be processed unless this processing is done under one of the six lawful bases specified by the regulation (consent, contract, public task, vital interest, legitimate interest or legal requirement).
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] When the processing is based on consent the data subject has the right to revoke it at any time.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A designated DPO can be a current member of staff of a controller or processor, or the role can be outsourced to an external person or agency through a service contract.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In any case, the processing body must make sure that there is no conflict of interest in other roles or interests that a DPO may hold.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The contact details for the DPO must be published by the processing organisation (for example, in a privacy notice) and registered with the supervisory authority.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The DPO is similar to a compliance officer and is also expected to be proficient at managing IT processes, data security (including dealing with cyberattacks) and other critical business continuity issues associated with the holding and processing of personal and sensitive data.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The skill set required stretches beyond understanding legal compliance with data protection laws and regulations.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The DPO must maintain a living data inventory of all data collected and stored on behalf of the organization.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] More details on the function and the role of data protection officer were given on 13 December 2016 (revised 5 April 2017) in a guideline document.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Organisations based outside the EU must also appoint an EU-based person as a representative and point of contact for their GDPR obligations.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This is a distinct role from a DPO, although there is overlap in responsibilities that suggest that this role can also be held by the designated DPO.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Article 42 and 43 of the GDPR set the legal basis for formal GDPR certifications.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] 42 GDPR, the purpose of this certification is to demonstrate “compliance with the GDPR of processing operations by controllers and processors”.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR certification also contributes to reduce the legal and financial risks of applicants, as well as of data controllers using certified data processing services.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The adoption of the European Data Protection Seals is under the responsibility of the European Data Protection Board (EDPB) and is recognized across all EU and EEA Member States.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In October 2022, the Europrivacy certification criteria were officially recognized by the European Data Protection Board (EDPB) to serve as European Data Protection Seal.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Europrivacy was developed by the European research programme and is managed by the European Centre for Certification and Privacy (ECCP) in Luxembourg.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] These are some cases which are not addressed in the GDPR specifically, thus are treated as exemptions.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Conversely, an entity or more precisely an "enterprise" has to be engaged in "economic activity" to be covered by the GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Economic activity is defined broadly under European Union competition law.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation applies regardless of where the processing takes place.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This has been interpreted as intentionally giving GDPR extraterritorial jurisdiction for non-EU establishments if they are doing business with people located in the EU.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is questionable whether the EU or its member states will in practice be able to enforce GDPR against organisations which have no establishment in the EU.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Under **Article 27**, non-EU establishments subject to GDPR are obliged to have a designee within the European Union, an "EU Representative", to serve as a point of contact for their obligations under the regulation.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The EU Representative is the Controller's or Processor's contact person vis-à-vis European privacy supervisors and data subjects, in all matters relating to processing, to ensure compliance with this GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A natural (individual) or legal (corporation) person can play the role of an EU Representative.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The non-EU establishment must issue a duly signed document (letter of accreditation) designating a given individual or company as its EU Representative.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The said designation can only be given in writing.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The intentional or negligent (willful blindness) character of the infringement (failure to designate an EU Representative) may rather constitute aggravating factors.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Non-EU public authorities and bodies are equally exempted.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Binding corporate rules, standard contractual clauses for data protection issued by a Data Processing Agreement (DPA), or a scheme of binding and enforceable commitments by the data controller or processor situated in a third country, are among examples.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The applicability of GDPR in the United Kingdom is affected by Brexit.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Although the United Kingdom formally withdrew from the European Union on 31 January 2020, it remained subject to EU law, including GDPR, until the end of the transition period on 31 December 2020.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Under the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018, existing and relevant EU law was transposed into UK law upon completion of the transition, and the GDPR was amended by statutory instrument to remove certain provisions no longer needed due to the UK's non-membership in the EU.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Thereafter, the regulation is referred to as "UK GDPR".
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The UK does not restrict the transfer of personal data to countries within the EEA under UK GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As part of the withdrawal agreement, the European Commission committed to perform an adequacy assessment.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] On 28 June 2021, the Commission confirmed the adequacy of the UK GDPR for four years; This was set to expire on 27 June 2025, but was extended for six months to give the Commission time to assess the impact of the Data (Use and Access) Act 2025.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] On 19 December 2025 the Commission renewed the 2021 adequacy decision until 27 December 2031.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In March 2021, Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Oliver Dowden stated that the UK was exploring divergence from the EU GDPR in order to "[focus] more on the outcomes that we want to have and less on the burdens of the rules imposed on individual businesses".
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As per a study conducted by Deloitte in 2018, 92% of companies believe they are able to comply with GDPR in their business practices in the long run.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Companies operating outside of the EU have invested heavily to align their business practices with GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The area of GDPR consent has a number of implications for businesses who record calls as a matter of practice.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A typical disclaimer is not considered sufficient to gain assumed consent to record calls.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Additionally, when recording has commenced, should the caller withdraw their consent, then the agent receiving the call must be able to stop a previously started recording and ensure the recording does not get stored.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] IT professionals expect that compliance with the GDPR will require additional investment overall: over 80 percent of those surveyed expected GDPR-related spending to be at least US$100,000.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It has been argued that smaller businesses and startup companies might not have the financial resources to adequately comply with the GDPR, unlike the larger international technology firms (such as Facebook and Google) that the regulation is ostensibly meant to target first and foremost.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A lack of knowledge and understanding of the regulations has also been a concern in the lead-up to its adoption.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A counter-argument to this has been that companies were made aware of these changes two years prior to them coming into effect and should have had enough time to prepare.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulations, including whether an enterprise must have a data protection officer, have been criticized for potential administrative burden and unclear compliance requirements.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There is also concern regarding the implementation of the GDPR in blockchain systems, as the transparent and fixed record of blockchain transactions contradicts the very nature of the GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Many media outlets have commented on the introduction of a "right to explanation" of algorithmic decisions, but legal scholars have since argued that the existence of such a right is highly unclear without judicial tests and is limited at best.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR has garnered support from businesses who regard it as an opportunity to improve their data management.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Mark Zuckerberg has also called it a "very positive step for the Internet", and has called for GDPR-style laws to be adopted in the US.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consumer rights groups such as The European Consumer Organisation are among the most vocal proponents of the legislation.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Other supporters have attributed its passage to the whistleblower Edward Snowden.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Free software advocate Richard Stallman has praised some aspects of the GDPR but called for additional safeguards to prevent technology companies from "manufacturing consent".
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Academic experts who participated in the formulation of the GDPR wrote that the law "is the most consequential regulatory development in information policy in a generation.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Despite having had at least two years to prepare and do so, many companies and websites changed their privacy policies and features worldwide directly prior to GDPR's implementation, and customarily provided email and other notifications discussing these changes.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Phishing scams also emerged using falsified versions of GDPR-related emails, and it was also argued that some GDPR notice emails may have actually been sent in violation of anti-spam laws.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In March 2019, a provider of compliance software found that many websites operated by EU member state governments contained embedded tracking from ad technology providers.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] A blog, *GDPR Hall of Shame*, was also created to showcase unusual delivery of GDPR notices, and attempts at compliance that contained egregious violations of the regulation's requirements.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Its author remarked that the regulation "has a lot of nitty gritty, in-the-weeds details, but not a lot of information about how to comply", but also acknowledged that businesses had two years to comply, making some of its responses unjustified.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Research indicates that approximately 25% of software vulnerabilities have GDPR implications.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Since Article 33 emphasizes breaches, not bugs, security experts advise companies to invest in processes and capabilities to identify vulnerabilities before they can be exploited, including coordinated vulnerability disclosure processes.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] An investigation of Android apps' privacy policies, data access capabilities, and data access behaviour has shown that numerous apps display a somewhat privacy-friendlier behaviour since the GDPR was implemented, although they still retain most of their data access privileges in their code.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] An investigation of the Norwegian Consumer Council into the post-GDPR data subject dashboards on social media platforms (such as Google dashboard) has concluded that large social media firms deploy deceptive tactics in order to discourage their customers from sharpening their privacy settings.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Some companies, such as Klout, and several online video games, ceased operations entirely to coincide with its implementation, citing the GDPR as a burden on their continued operations, especially due to the business model of the former.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The volume of online behavioural advertising placements in Europe fell 25–40% on 25 May 2018.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Facebook and subsidiaries WhatsApp and Instagram, as well as Google LLC (targeting Android), were immediately sued by Max Schrems's non-profit NOYB just hours after midnight on 25 May 2018, for their use of "forced consent".
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Schrems asserts that both companies violated Article 7(4) by not presenting opt-ins for data processing consent on an individualized basis, and requiring users to consent to all data processing activities (including those not strictly necessary) or would be forbidden from using the services.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] On 21 January 2019, Google was fined €50 million by the French DPA for showing insufficient control, consent, and transparency over use of personal data for behavioural advertising.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In November 2018, following a journalistic investigation into Liviu Dragnea, the Romanian DPA (ANSPDCP) used a GDPR request to demand information on the RISE Project's sources.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In July 2019, the British Information Commissioner's Office issued an intention to fine British Airways a record £183 million (1.5% of turnover) for poor security arrangements that enabled a 2018 web skimming attack affecting around 380,000 transactions.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] British Airways was ultimately fined a reduced amount of £20m, with the ICO noting that they had "considered both representations from BA and the economic impact of COVID-19 on their business before setting a final penalty".
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Critics interviewed by *Politico* also argued that enforcement was also being hampered by varying interpretations between member states, the prioritisation of guidance over enforcement by some authorities, and a lack of cooperation between member states.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In November 2021, Irish Council for Civil Liberties lodged a formal complaint of the Commission that it is in breach of its obligation under EU Law to carefully monitor how Ireland applies the GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Until January 2023, the Commission published a new commitment based on the complaint of ICCL.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] While companies are now subject to legal obligations, there are still various inconsistencies in the practical and technical implementation of GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As an example, according to the GDPR's right to access, the companies are obliged to provide data subjects with the data they gather about them.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] However, in a study on loyalty cards in Germany, companies did not provide the data subjects with the exact information of the purchased articles.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] One might argue that such companies do not collect the information of the purchased articles, which does not conform with their business models.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Therefore, data subjects tend to see that as a GDPR violation.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As a result, studies have suggested for a better control through authorities.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] According to the GDPR, end-users' consent should be valid, freely given, specific, informed and active.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] However, the lack of enforceability regarding obtaining lawful consents has been a challenge.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple, and Microsoft (GAFAM), use dark patterns in their consent obtaining mechanisms, which raises doubts regarding the lawfulness of the acquired consent.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In March 2021, EU member states led by France were reported to be attempting to modify the impact of the privacy regulation in Europe by exempting national security agencies.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] After around 160 million Euros in GDPR fines were imposed in 2020, the figure was already over one billion Euros in 2021.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In 2024 and early 2025, GDPR enforcement actions intensified.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The Irish Data Protection Commission (DPC) imposed a €345 million fine on TikTok for violations related to children's data privacy and insufficient safeguards for young users.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In January 2025, Meta was fined €1.2 billion for unlawful data transfers between the EU and the US, marking one of the largest GDPR fines to date.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] On 12 February 2025, the European Commission abandoned proposed regulations on technology patents, AI liability, and privacy for messaging apps due to strong lobbying and a lack of consensus among EU lawmakers, with major tech firms opposing the changes.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Mass adoption of these new privacy standards by multinational companies has been cited as an example of the "Brussels effect", a phenomenon wherein European laws and regulations are used as a baseline due to their gravitas.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The U.S. state of California passed the California Consumer Privacy Act on 28 June 2018, taking effect on 1 January 2020; it grants rights to transparency and control over the collection of personal information by companies in a similar means to GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Critics have argued that such laws need to be implemented at the federal level to be effective, as a collection of state-level laws would have varying standards that would complicate compliance.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Two other U.S. states have since enacted similar legislation: Virginia passed the Consumer Data Privacy Act on 2 March 2021, and Colorado enacted the Colorado Privacy Act on 8 July 2021.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The Republic of Turkey, a candidate for European Union membership, adopted the Law on The Protection of Personal Data on 24 March 2016 in compliance with the EU acquis.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] China's 2021 Personal Information Protection Law is the country's first comprehensive law on personal data rights and is modelled after the GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Switzerland will also adopt a new data protection law that largely follows EU's GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The CLOUD Act, enacted in 2018, is seen by the European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) as a law in possible conflict with the GDPR.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] A 2024 study found that GDPR reduced both EU user website page views and website revenue by 12%.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The EU Digital Single Market strategy relates to "digital economy" activities related to businesses and people in the EU.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As part of the strategy, the GDPR and the NIS Directive all apply from 25 May 2018.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The proposed ePrivacy Regulation was also planned to be applicable from 25 May 2018, but will be delayed for several months.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The eIDAS Regulation is also part of the strategy.
[src:consent-management/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In an initial assessment, the European Council has stated that the GDPR should be considered "a prerequisite for the development of future digital policy initiatives".
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] An **HTTP cookie** (also called **web cookie**, **Internet cookie**, **browser cookie**, or simply **cookie**) is a small block of data created by a web server while a user is browsing a website and placed on the user's computer or other device by the user's web browser.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are placed on the device used to access a website, and more than one cookie may be placed on a user's device during a session.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies serve useful and sometimes essential functions on the web.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] They enable web servers to store stateful information (such as items added in the shopping cart in an online store) on the user's device or to track the user's browsing activity (including clicking particular buttons, logging in, or recording which pages were visited in the past).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] They can also be used to save information that the user previously entered into form fields, such as names, addresses, passwords, and payment card numbers for subsequent use.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie* was coined by web-browser programmer Lou Montulli.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] It was derived from the term *magic cookie*, which is a packet of data a program receives and sends back unchanged, used by Unix programmers.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Magic cookies were already used in computing when computer programmer Lou Montulli had the idea of using them in web communications in June 1994.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] At the time, he was an employee of Netscape Communications, which was developing an e-commerce application for MCI.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Vint Cerf and John Klensin represented MCI in technical discussions with Netscape Communications.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] MCI did not want its servers to have to retain partial transaction states, which led them to ask Netscape to find a way to store that state in each user's computer instead.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies provided a solution to the problem of reliably implementing a virtual shopping cart.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Together with John Giannandrea, Montulli wrote the initial Netscape cookie specification the same year.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Version 0.9beta of Mosaic Netscape, released on 13 October 1994, supported cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The first use of cookies (out of the labs) was checking whether visitors to the Netscape website had already visited the site.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Montulli applied for a patent for the cookie technology in 1995, which was granted in 1998.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Support for cookies was integrated with Internet Explorer in version 2, released in October 1995.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The introduction of cookies was not widely known to the public at the time.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In particular, cookies were accepted by default, and users were not notified of their presence.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The public learned about cookies after the *Financial Times* published an article about them on 12 February 1996.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In the same year, cookies received a lot of media attention, especially because of potential privacy implications.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Federal Trade Commission hearings in 1996 and 1997.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The development of the formal cookie specifications was already ongoing.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In particular, the first discussions about a formal specification started in April 1995 on the www-talk mailing list.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A special working group within the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) was formed.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Two alternative proposals for introducing state in HTTP transactions had been proposed by Brian Behlendorf and David Kristol respectively.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] But the group, headed by Kristol himself and Lou Montulli, soon decided to use the Netscape specification as a starting point.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In February 1996, the working group identified third-party cookies as a considerable privacy threat.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The specification produced by the group was eventually published as RFC 2109 in February 1997.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] It specifies that third-party cookies were either not allowed at all, or at least not enabled by default.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] At this time, advertising companies were already using third-party cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The recommendation about third-party cookies of RFC 2109 was not followed by Netscape and Internet Explorer.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2109 was superseded by RFC 2965 in October 2000.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2965 added a `Set-Cookie2` header field, which informally came to be called "RFC 2965-style cookies" as opposed to the original `Set-Cookie` header field which was called "Netscape-style cookies".
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] `Set-Cookie2` was seldom used, however, and was deprecated in RFC 6265 in April 2011 which was written as a definitive specification for cookies as used in the real world.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] No modern browser recognizes the `Set-Cookie2` header field.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A *session cookie* (also known as an *in-memory cookie*, *transient cookie* or *non-persistent cookie*) exists only in temporary memory while the user navigates a website.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies expire or are deleted when the user closes the web browser.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are identified by the browser by the absence of an expiration date assigned to them.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A *persistent cookie* expires at a specific date or after a specific length of time.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For the persistent cookie's lifespan set by its creator, its information will be transmitted to the server every time the user visits the website that it belongs to, or every time the user views a resource belonging to that website from another website (such as an advertisement).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, persistent cookies are sometimes referred to as *tracking cookies* because they can be used by advertisers to record information about a user's web browsing habits over an extended period of time.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Persistent cookies are also used for reasons such as keeping users logged into their accounts on websites, to avoid re-entering login credentials at every visit.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A *secure cookie* can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection (i.e.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] They cannot be transmitted over unencrypted connections (i.e.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This makes the cookie less likely to be exposed to cookie theft via eavesdropping.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is made secure by adding the `Secure` flag to the cookie.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] An *http-only cookie* cannot be accessed by client-side APIs, such as JavaScript.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This restriction eliminates the threat of cookie theft via cross-site scripting (XSS).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] However, the cookie remains vulnerable to cross-site tracing (XST) and cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is given this characteristic by adding the `HttpOnly` flag to the cookie.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In 2016 Google Chrome version 51 introduced a new kind of cookie with attribute `SameSite` with possible values of `Strict`, `Lax` or `None`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] With attribute `SameSite=Strict`, the browsers would only send cookies to a target domain that is the same as the origin domain.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This would effectively mitigate cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] With `SameSite=Lax`, browsers would send cookies with requests to a target domain even it is different from the origin domain, but only for *safe* requests such as GET (POST is unsafe) and not third-party cookies (inside iframe).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Attribute `SameSite=None` would allow third-party (cross-site) cookies, however, most browsers require secure attribute on SameSite=None cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The Same-site cookie is incorporated into a new RFC draft for "Cookies: HTTP State Management Mechanism" to update RFC 6265 (if approved).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Chrome, Firefox, and Edge started to support Same-site cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The key of rollout is the treatment of existing cookies without the SameSite attribute defined, Chrome has been treating those existing cookies as if SameSite=None, this would let all website/applications run as before.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Google intended to change that default to `SameSite=Lax` in Chrome 80 planned to be released in February 2020, but due to potential for breakage of those applications/websites that rely on third-party/cross-site cookies and COVID-19 circumstances, Google postponed this change to Chrome 84.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A *supercookie* is a cookie with an origin of a top-level domain (such as `.com`) or a public suffix (such as `.co.uk`).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Ordinary cookies, by contrast, have an origin of a specific domain name, such as `example.com`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Supercookies can be a potential security concern and are therefore often blocked by web browsers.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] If unblocked by the browser, an attacker in control of a malicious website could set a supercookie and potentially disrupt or impersonate legitimate user requests to another website that shares the same top-level domain or public suffix as the malicious website.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For example, a supercookie with an origin of `.com` could maliciously affect a request made to `example.com`, even if the cookie did not originate from `example.com`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This can be used to fake logins or change user information.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List helps to mitigate the risk that supercookies pose.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List is a cross-vendor initiative that aims to provide an accurate and up-to-date list of domain name suffixes.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Older versions of browsers may not have an up-to-date list, and will therefore be vulnerable to supercookies from certain domains.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The term *supercookie* is also used for tracking technologies that do not rely on HTTP cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Two such *supercookie* mechanisms were found on Microsoft websites in August 2011: cookie syncing that respawned MUID (machine unique identifier) cookies, and ETag cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Due to media attention, Microsoft later disabled this code.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In a 2021 blog post, Mozilla used the term *supercookie* to refer to the use of browser cache as a means of tracking users across sites.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Zero or more attributes (name/value pairs).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Attributes store information such as the cookie's expiration, domain, and flags (such as `Secure` and `HttpOnly`).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies were originally introduced to provide a way for users to record items they want to purchase as they navigate throughout a website (a virtual *shopping cart* or *shopping basket*).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Today, however, the contents of a user's shopping cart are usually stored in a database on the server, rather than in a cookie on the client.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] To keep track of which user is assigned to which shopping cart, the server sends a cookie to the client that contains a unique session identifier (typically, a long string of random letters and numbers).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Because cookies are sent to the server with every request the client makes, that session identifier will be sent back to the server every time the user visits a new page on the website, which lets the server know which shopping cart to display to the user.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Another popular use of cookies is for logging into websites.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] When the user visits a website's login page, the web server typically sends the client a cookie containing a unique session identifier.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] When the user successfully logs in, the server remembers that that particular session identifier has been authenticated and grants the user access to its services.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Because session cookies only contain a unique session identifier, this makes the amount of personal information that a website can save about each user virtually limitless—the website is not limited to restrictions concerning how large a cookie can be.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies also help to improve page load times, since the amount of information in a session cookie is small and requires little bandwidth.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can be used to remember information about the user in order to show relevant content to that user over time.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For example, a web server might send a cookie containing the username that was last used to log into a website, so that it may be filled in automatically the next time the user logs in.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Many websites use cookies for personalization based on the user's preferences.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Users select their preferences by entering them in a web form and submitting the form to the server.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The server encodes the preferences in a cookie and sends the cookie back to the browser.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This way, every time the user accesses a page on the website, the server can personalize the page according to the user's preferences.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For example, the Google search engine once used cookies to allow users (even non-registered ones) to decide how many search results per page they wanted to see.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Also, DuckDuckGo uses cookies to allow users to set the viewing preferences like colors of the web page.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Tracking cookies are used to track users' web browsing habits.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This can also be done to some extent by using the IP address of the computer requesting the page or the referer field of the HTTP request header, but cookies allow for greater precision.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] From this point on, the cookie will automatically be sent by the browser to the server every time a new page from the site is requested.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The server not only sends the page as usual but also stores the URL of the requested page, the date/time of the request, and the cookie in a log file.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] By analyzing this log file, it is then possible to discover which pages the user has visited, in what sequence, and for how long.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Corporations exploit users' web habits by tracking cookies to collect information about buying habits.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The *Wall Street Journal* found that America's top fifty websites installed an average of sixty-four pieces of tracking technology onto computers, resulting in a total of 3,180 tracking files.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The data can then be collected and sold to bidding corporations.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are arbitrary pieces of data, usually chosen and first sent by the web server, and stored on the client computer by the web browser.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The browser then sends them back to the server with every request, introducing states (memory of previous events) into otherwise stateless HTTP transactions.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Without cookies, each retrieval of a web page or component of a web page would be an isolated event, largely unrelated to all other page views made by the user on the website.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Although cookies are usually set by the web server, they can also be set by the client using a scripting language such as JavaScript (unless the cookie's `HttpOnly` flag is set, in which case the cookie cannot be modified by scripting languages).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are set using the `Set-Cookie` header field, sent in an HTTP response from the web server.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This header field instructs the web browser to store the cookie and send it back in future requests to the server (the browser will ignore this header field if it does not support cookies or has disabled cookies).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The server's HTTP response contains the contents of the website's homepage.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] But it also instructs the browser to set two cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The first, *theme*, is considered to be a *session cookie* since it does not have an `Expires` or `Max-Age` attribute.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are intended to be deleted by the browser when the browser closes.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The second, *sessionToken*, is considered to be a *persistent cookie* since it contains an `Expires` attribute, which instructs the browser to delete the cookie at a specific date and time.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Next, the browser sends another request to visit the `spec.html` page on the website.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This way, the server knows that this HTTP request is related to the previous one.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The server would answer by sending the requested page, possibly including more `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response in order to instruct the browser to add new cookies, modify existing cookies, or remove existing cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] To remove a cookie, the server must include a `Set-Cookie` header field with an expiration date in the past.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The value of a cookie may consist of any printable ASCII character (`!` through `~`, Unicode `\u0021` through `\u007E`) excluding `,`and`;` and whitespace characters.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The name of a cookie excludes the same characters, as well as `=`, since that is the delimiter between the name and value.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The cookie standard RFC 2965 is more restrictive but not implemented by browsers.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie crumb* is sometimes used to refer to a cookie's name–value pair.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be set by scripting languages such as JavaScript that run within the browser.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In JavaScript, the object `document.cookie` is used for this purpose.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For example, the instruction `document.cookie = "temperature=20"` creates a cookie of name *temperature* and value *20*.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In addition to a name and value, cookies can also have one or more attributes.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Browsers do not include cookie attributes in requests to the server—they only send the cookie's name and value.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookie attributes are used by browsers to determine when to delete a cookie, block a cookie or whether to send a cookie to the server.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The `Domain` and `Path` attributes define the scope of the cookie.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] They essentially tell the browser what website the cookie belongs to.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For security reasons, cookies can only be set on the current resource's top domain and its subdomains, and not for another domain and its subdomains.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For example, the website `example.org` cannot set a cookie that has a domain of `foo.com` because this would allow the website `example.org` to control the cookies of the domain `foo.com`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] If a cookie's `Domain` and `Path` attributes are not specified by the server, they default to the domain and path of the resource that was requested.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] However, in most browsers there is a difference between a cookie set from `foo.com` without a domain, and a cookie set with the `foo.com` domain.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In the former case, the cookie will only be sent for requests to `foo.com`, also known as a host-only cookie.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In the latter case, all subdomains are also included (for example, `docs.foo.com`).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A notable exception to this general rule is Edge prior to Windows 10 RS3 and Internet Explorer prior to IE 11 and Windows 10 RS4 (April 2018), which always sends cookies to subdomains regardless of whether the cookie was set with or without a domain.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Below is an example of some `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response of a website after a user logged in.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `LSID`, has no `Domain` attribute, and has a `Path` attribute set to `/accounts`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This tells the browser to use the cookie only when requesting pages contained in `docs.foo.com/accounts` (the domain is derived from the request domain).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The other two cookies, `HSID` and `SSID`, would be used when the browser requests any subdomain in `.foo.com` on any path (for example `www.foo.com/bar`).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The prepending dot is optional in recent standards, but can be added for compatibility with RFC 2109 based implementations.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The `Expires` attribute defines a specific date and time for when the browser should delete the cookie.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The date and time are specified in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YYYY HH:MM:SS GMT`, or in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YY HH:MM:SS GMT` for values of YY where YY is greater than or equal to 0 and less than or equal to 69.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Alternatively, the `Max-Age` attribute can be used to set the cookie's expiration as an interval of seconds in the future, relative to the time the browser received the cookie.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `lu`, is set to expire sometime on 15 January 2013.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] It will be used by the client browser until that time.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The second cookie, `made_write_conn`, does not have an expiration date, making it a session cookie.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] It will be deleted after the user closes their browser.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The third cookie, `reg_fb_gate`, has its value changed to *deleted*, with an expiration time in the past.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The browser will delete this cookie right away because its expiration time is in the past.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Note that cookie will only be deleted if the domain and path attributes in the `Set-Cookie` field match the values used when the cookie was created.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] As of 2016 Internet Explorer did not support `Max-Age`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` and `HttpOnly` attributes do not have associated values.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Rather, the presence of just their attribute names indicates that their behaviors should be enabled.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` attribute is meant to keep cookie communication limited to encrypted transmission, directing browsers to use cookies only via secure/encrypted connections.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] However, if a web server sets a cookie with a secure attribute from a non-secure connection, the cookie can still be intercepted when it is sent to the user by man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Therefore, for maximum security, cookies with the Secure attribute should only be set over a secure connection.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The `HttpOnly` attribute directs browsers not to expose cookies through channels other than HTTP (and HTTPS) requests.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This means that the cookie cannot be accessed via client-side scripting languages (notably JavaScript), and therefore cannot be stolen easily via cross-site scripting (a pervasive attack technique).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Most modern browsers support cookies and allow the user to disable them.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Add-on tools for managing cookie permissions also exist.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies have some important implications for the privacy and anonymity of web users.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] While cookies are sent only to the server setting them or a server in the same Internet domain, a web page may contain images or other components stored on servers in other domains.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies that are set during retrieval of these components are called *third-party cookies*.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A third-party cookie, belongs to a domain different from the one shown in the address bar.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This sort of cookie typically appears when web pages feature content from external websites, such as banner advertisements.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This opens up the potential for tracking the user's browsing history and is used by advertisers to serve relevant advertisements to each user.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] As an example, suppose a user visits `www.example.org`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This website contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com`, which, when downloaded, sets a cookie belonging to the advertisement's domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Then, the user visits another website, `www.foo.com`, which also contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com` and sets a cookie belonging to that domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Eventually, both of these cookies will be sent to the advertiser when loading their advertisements or visiting their website.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The advertiser can then use these cookies to build up a browsing history of the user across all the websites that have ads from this advertiser, through the use of the HTTP referer header field.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] As of 2014, some websites were setting cookies readable for over 100 third-party domains.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] On average, a single website was setting 10 cookies, with a maximum number of cookies (first- and third-party) reaching over 800.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The older standards for cookies, RFC 2109 and RFC 2965, recommend that browsers should protect user privacy and not allow sharing of cookies between servers by default.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] However, the newer standard, RFC 6265, explicitly allows user agents to implement whichever third-party cookie policy they wish.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Most modern web browsers contain privacy settings that can block third-party cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Since 2020, Apple Safari, Firefox, and Brave block all third-party cookies by default.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Safari allows embedded sites to use Storage Access API to request permission to set first-party cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In May 2020, Google Chrome 83 introduced new features to block third-party cookies by default in its Incognito mode for private browsing, making blocking optional during normal browsing.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The same update also added an option to block first-party cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In April 2024, Chrome postponed third-party cookie blocking by default to 2025.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In July 2024, Google announced plan to avoid blocking third-party cookies by default and instead prompt users to allow third-party cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The possibility of building a profile of users is a privacy threat, especially when tracking is done across multiple domains using third-party cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, some countries have legislation about cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Website operators who do not disclose third-party cookie use to consumers run the risk of harming consumer trust if cookie use is discovered.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Having clear disclosure (such as in a privacy policy) tends to eliminate any negative effects of such cookie discovery.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The government of the United States set strict rules on setting cookies in 2000 after it was disclosed that the White House drug policy office used cookies to track computer users viewing its online anti-drug advertising.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, privacy activist Daniel Brandt found that the CIA had been leaving persistent cookies on computers that had visited its website.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] When notified it was violating policy, CIA stated that these cookies were not intentionally set and stopped setting them.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] On 25 December 2005, Brandt discovered that the National Security Agency (NSA) had been leaving two persistent cookies on visitors' computers due to a software upgrade.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] After being informed, the NSA immediately disabled the cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, the European Union launched the Directive on Privacy and Electronic Communications (e-Privacy Directive), a policy requiring end users' consent for the placement of cookies, and similar technologies for storing and accessing information on users' equipment.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In particular, Article 5 Paragraph 3 mandates that storing technically unnecessary data on a user's computer can only be done if the user is provided information about how this data is used, and the user is given the possibility of denying this storage operation.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The Directive does not require users to authorise or be provided notice of cookie usage that are functionally required for delivering a service they have requested, for example to retain settings, store log-in sessions, or remember what is in a user's shopping basket.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In 2009, the law was amended by Directive 2009/136/EC, which included a change to Article 5, Paragraph 3.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Instead of having an option for users to opt out of cookie storage, the revised Directive requires consent to be obtained for cookie storage.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The definition of consent is cross-referenced to the definition in European data protection law, firstly the Data Protection Directive 1995 and subsequently the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] As the definition of consent was strengthened in the text of the GDPR, this increased the quality of consent required by those storing and accessing information such as cookies on users devices.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In a case decided under the Data Protection Directive however, the Court of Justice of the European Union later confirmed however that the previous law implied the same strong quality of consent as the current instrument.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In addition to the requirement of consent which stems from storing or accessing information on a user's terminal device, the information in many cookies will be considered personal data under the GDPR alone, and will require a legal basis to process.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This has been the case since the 1995 Data Protection Directive, which used an identical definition of personal data, although the GDPR in interpretative Recital 30 clarifies that cookie identifiers are included.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] While not all data processing under the GDPR requires consent, the characteristics of behavioural advertising mean that it is difficult or impossible to justify under any other ground.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Consent under the combination of the GDPR and e-Privacy Directive has to meet a number of conditions in relation to cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] It must be freely given and unambiguous: preticked boxes were banned under both the Data Protection Directive 1995 and the GDPR (Recital 32).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The GDPR is specific that consent must be as 'easy to withdraw as to give', meaning that a reject-all button must be as easy to access in terms of clicks and visibility as an 'accept all' button.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] It must be specific and informed, meaning that consent relates to particular purposes for the use of this data, and all organisations seeking to use this consent must be specifically named.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The Court of Justice of the European Union has also ruled that consent must be 'efficient and timely', meaning that it must be gained before cookies are laid and data processing begins instead of afterwards.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The industry's response has been largely negative.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Robert Bond of the law firm Speechly Bircham describes the effects as "far-reaching and incredibly onerous" for "all UK companies".
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Simon Davis of Privacy International argues that proper enforcement would "destroy the entire industry".
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] However, scholars note that the onerous nature of cookie pop-ups stems from an attempt to continue to operate a business model through convoluted requests that may be incompatible with the GDPR.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Academic studies and regulators both describe widespread non-compliance with the law.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A study scraping 10,000 UK websites found that only 11.8% of sites adhered to minimal legal requirements, with only 33.4% of websites studied providing a mechanism to reject cookies that was as easy to use as accepting them.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A study of 17,000 websites found that 84% of sites breached this criterion, finding additionally that many laid third party cookies with no notice at all.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A W3C specification called P3P was proposed for servers to communicate their privacy policy to browsers, allowing automatic, user-configurable handling.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] However, few websites implement the specification, and the W3C has discontinued work on the specification.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Third-party cookies can be blocked by most browsers to increase privacy and reduce tracking by advertising and tracking companies without negatively affecting the user's web experience on all sites.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Some sites operate 'cookie walls', which make access to a site conditional on allowing cookies either technically in a browser, through pressing 'accept', or both.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In 2020, the European Data Protection Board, composed of all EU data protection regulators, stated that cookie walls were illegal.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Many advertising operators have an opt-out option to behavioural advertising, with a generic cookie in the browser stopping behavioural advertising.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] However, this is often ineffective against many forms of tracking, such as first-party tracking that is growing in popularity to avoid the impact of browsers blocking third party cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Furthermore, if such a setting is more difficult to place than the acceptance of tracking, it remains in breach of the conditions of the e-Privacy Directive.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Most websites use cookies as the only identifiers for user sessions, because other methods of identifying web users have limitations and vulnerabilities.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] If a website uses cookies as session identifiers, attackers can impersonate users' requests by stealing a full set of victims' cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] From the web server's point of view, a request from an attacker then has the same authentication as the victim's requests; thus the request is performed on behalf of the victim's session.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Listed here are various scenarios of cookie theft and user session hijacking (even without stealing user cookies) that work with websites relying solely on HTTP cookies for user identification.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Traffic on a network can be intercepted and read by computers on the network other than the sender and receiver (particularly over unencrypted open Wi-Fi).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This traffic includes cookies sent on ordinary unencrypted HTTP sessions.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Where network traffic is not encrypted, attackers can therefore read the communications of other users on the network, including HTTP cookies as well as the entire contents of the conversations, for the purpose of a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] An attacker could use intercepted cookies to impersonate a user and perform a malicious task, such as transferring money out of the victim's bank account.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This issue can be resolved by securing the communication between the user's computer and the server by employing Transport Layer Security (HTTPS protocol) to encrypt the connection.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] A server can specify the `Secure` flag while setting a cookie, which will cause the browser to send the cookie only over an encrypted channel, such as a TLS connection.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to cause a DNS server to cache a fabricated DNS entry (called DNS cache poisoning), then this could allow the attacker to gain access to a user's cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For example, an attacker could use DNS cache poisoning to create a fabricated DNS entry of `f12345.www.example.com` that points to the IP address of the attacker's server.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The attacker can then post an image URL from his own server (for example, `http://f12345.www.example.com/img_4_cookie.jpg`).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Victims reading the attacker's message would download this image from `f12345.www.example.com`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Since `f12345.www.example.com` is a sub-domain of `www.example.com`, victims' browsers would submit all `example.com`-related cookies to the attacker's server.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to accomplish this, it is usually the fault of the Internet service providers for not properly securing their DNS servers.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] However, the severity of this attack can be lessened if the target website uses secure cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the attacker would have the extra challenge of obtaining the target website's TLS certificate from a certificate authority, since secure cookies can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Without a matching TLS certificate, victims' browsers would display a warning message about the attacker's invalid certificate, which would help deter users from visiting the attacker's fraudulent website and sending the attacker their cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be stolen using a technique called cross-site scripting.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This occurs when an attacker takes advantage of a website that allows its users to post unfiltered HTML and JavaScript content.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] By posting malicious HTML and JavaScript code, the attacker can cause the victim's web browser to send the victim's cookies to a website the attacker controls.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] When another user clicks on this link, the browser executes the piece of code within the `onclick` attribute, thus replacing the string `document.cookie` with the list of cookies that are accessible from the current page.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] As a result, this list of cookies is sent to the `attacker.com` server.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] If the attacker's malicious posting is on an HTTPS website `https://www.example.com`, secure cookies will also be sent to attacker.com in plain text.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] It is the responsibility of the website developers to filter out such malicious code.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Such attacks can be mitigated by using HttpOnly cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] These cookies will not be accessible by client-side scripting languages like JavaScript, and therefore, the attacker will not be able to gather these cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In older versions of many browsers, there were security holes in the implementation of the XMLHttpRequest API.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This API allows pages to specify a proxy server that would get the reply, and this proxy server is not subject to the same-origin policy.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For example, a victim is reading an attacker's posting on `www.example.com`, and the attacker's script is executed in the victim's browser.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] The script generates a request to `www.example.com` with the proxy server `attacker.com`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Since the request is for `www.example.com`, all `example.com` cookies will be sent along with the request, but routed through the attacker's proxy server.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Hence, the attacker would be able to harvest the victim's cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] This attack would not work with secure cookies, since they can only be transmitted over HTTPS connections, and the HTTPS protocol dictates end-to-end encryption (i.e. the information is encrypted on the user's browser and decrypted on the destination server).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the proxy server would only see the raw, encrypted bytes of the HTTP request.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] For example, Bob might be browsing a chat forum where another user, Mallory, has posted a message.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] If Bob's bank keeps his authentication information in a cookie, and if the cookie hasn't expired, then the attempt by Bob's browser to load the image will submit the withdrawal form with his cookie, thus authorizing a transaction without Bob's approval.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Besides privacy concerns, cookies also have some technical drawbacks.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] In particular, they do not always accurately identify users, they can be used for security attacks, and they are often at odds with the Representational State Transfer (REST) software architectural style.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] If more than one browser is used on a computer, each usually has a separate storage area for cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Hence, cookies do not identify a person, but a combination of a user account, a computer, and a web browser.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Thus, anyone who uses multiple accounts, computers, or browsers has multiple sets of cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p01] Likewise, cookies do not differentiate between multiple users who share the same user account, computer, and browser.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Some of the operations that can be done using cookies can also be done using other mechanisms.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] A JSON Web Token (JWT) is a self-contained packet of information that can be used to store user identity and authenticity information.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] This allows them to be used in place of session cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Unlike cookies, which are automatically attached to each HTTP request by the browser, JWTs must be explicitly attached to each HTTP request by the web application.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] The HTTP protocol includes the basic access authentication and the digest access authentication protocols, which allow access to a web page only when the user has provided the correct username and password.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] If the server requires such credentials for granting access to a web page, the browser requests them from the user and, once obtained, the browser stores and sends them in every subsequent page request.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] This information can be used to track the user.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] The query string part of the URL is the part that is typically used for this purpose, but other parts can be used as well.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] The Java Servlet and PHP session mechanisms both use this method if cookies are not enabled.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] This method consists of the web server appending query strings containing a unique session identifier to all the links inside of a web page.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] When the user follows a link, the browser sends the query string to the server, allowing the server to identify the user and maintain state.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] These kinds of query strings are very similar to cookies in that both contain arbitrary pieces of information chosen by the server and both are sent back to the server on every request.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Since a query string is part of a URL, if that URL is later reused, the same attached piece of information will be sent to the server, which could lead to confusion.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] For example, if the preferences of a user are encoded in the query string of a URL and the user sends this URL to another user by e-mail, those preferences will be used for that other user as well.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Moreover, if the same user accesses the same page multiple times from different sources, there is no guarantee that the same query string will be used each time.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] For example, if a user visits a page by coming from a page *internal to the site* the first time, and then visits the same page by coming from an *external search engine* the second time, the query strings would likely be different.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] If cookies were used in this situation, the cookies would be the same.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Other drawbacks of query strings are related to security.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Storing data that identifies a session in a query string enables session fixation attacks, referer logging attacks and other security exploits.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Transferring session identifiers as HTTP cookies is more secure.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Another form of session tracking is to use web forms with hidden fields.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] This technique is very similar to using URL query strings to hold the information and has many of the same advantages and drawbacks.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] In fact, if the form is handled with the HTTP GET method, then this technique is similar to using URL query strings, since the GET method adds the form fields to the URL as a query string.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] But most forms are handled with HTTP POST, which causes the form information, including the hidden fields, to be sent in the HTTP request body, which is neither part of the URL, nor of a cookie.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] This approach presents two advantages from the point of view of the tracker.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] First, having the tracking information placed in the HTTP request body rather than in the URL means it will not be noticed by the average user.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Second, the session information is not copied when the user copies the URL (to bookmark the page or send it via email, for example).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] All current web browsers can store a fairly large amount of data (2–32 MB) via JavaScript using the DOM property `window.name`.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] This data can be used instead of session cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] The technique can be coupled with JSON/JavaScript objects to store complex sets of session variables on the client side.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] The downside is that every separate window or tab will initially have an empty `window.name` property when opened.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] In some respects, this can be more secure than cookies because its contents are not automatically sent to the server on every request like cookies are, so it is not vulnerable to network cookie sniffing attacks.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Some users may be tracked based on the IP address of the computer requesting the page.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] The server knows the IP address of the computer running the browser (or the proxy, if any is used) and could theoretically link a user's session to this IP address.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] However, IP addresses are generally not a reliable way to track a session or identify a user.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Many computers designed to be used by a single user, such as office PCs or home PCs, are behind a network address translator (NAT).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] This means that several PCs will share a public IP address.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Furthermore, some systems, such as Tor, are designed to retain Internet anonymity, rendering tracking by IP address impractical, impossible, or a security risk.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Because ETags are cached by the browser, and returned with subsequent requests for the same resource, a tracking server can simply repeat any ETag received from the browser to ensure an assigned ETag persists indefinitely (in a similar way to persistent cookies).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Additional caching header fields can also enhance the preservation of ETag data.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] ETags can be flushed in some browsers by clearing the browser cache.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] The browser cache can also be used to store information that can be used to track individual users.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] This technique takes advantage of the fact that the web browser will use resources stored within the cache instead of downloading them from the website when it determines that the cache already has the most up-to-date version of the resource.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] For example, a website could serve a JavaScript file with code that sets a unique identifier for the user (for example, `var userId = 3243242;`).
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] After the user's initial visit, every time the user accesses the page, this file will be loaded from the cache instead of downloaded from the server.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] A browser fingerprint is information collected about a browser's configuration, such as version number, screen resolution, and operating system, for the purpose of identification.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Fingerprints can be used to fully or partially identify individual users or devices even when cookies are turned off.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Basic web browser configuration information has long been collected by web analytics services in an effort to accurately measure real human web traffic and discount various forms of click fraud.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] With the assistance of client-side scripting languages, collection of much more esoteric parameters is possible.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Assimilation of such information into a single string constitutes a device fingerprint.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] In 2010, EFF measured at least 18.1 bits of entropy possible from browser fingerprinting.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Canvas fingerprinting, a more recent technique, claims to add another 5.7 bits.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Some web browsers support persistence mechanisms which allow the page to store the information locally for later use.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] The HTML5 standard (which most modern web browsers support to some extent) includes a JavaScript API called Web storage that allows two types of storage: local storage and session storage.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Local storage behaves similarly to persistent cookies while session storage behaves similarly to session cookies, except that session storage is tied to an individual tab/window's lifetime (AKA a page session), not to a whole browser session like session cookies.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Internet Explorer supports persistent information in the browser's history, in the browser's favorites, in an XML store ("user data"), or directly within a web page saved to disk.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] Some web browser plugins include persistence mechanisms as well.
[src:consent-management/http-cookie-p02] For example, Adobe Flash has Local shared object and Microsoft Silverlight has Isolated storage.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Within the United States, definitions of informed consent vary, and the standard required is generally determined by the state.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] As of 2016, nearly half of the states adopted a reasonable patient standard, in which the informed consent process is viewed from the patient's perspective.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] These standards in medical contexts are formalized in the requirement for decision-making capacity and professional determinations in these contexts have legal authority.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Understanding, the capacity to apprehend the relevant facts pertaining to the decision at issue.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Appreciation, the ability of the patient to give informed consent with concern for, and belief in, the impact the relevant facts will have upon oneself.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Reasoning, the mental acuity to make the relevant inferences from, and mental manipulations of, the information appreciated and understood to apply to the decision at hand.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Impairments to reasoning and judgment that may preclude informed consent include intellectual or emotional immaturity, high levels of stress such as post-traumatic stress disorder or a severe intellectual disability, severe mental disorder, intoxication, severe sleep deprivation, dementia, or coma.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Obtaining informed consent is not always required.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Alternatively, the doctrine of implied consent permits treatment in limited cases, for example when an unconscious person will die without immediate intervention.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Cases in which an individual is provided insufficient information to form a reasoned decision raise serious ethical issues.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] When these issues occur, or are anticipated to occur, in a clinical trial, they are subject to review by an ethics committee or institutional review board.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Informed consent is codified in both national and international law.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] 'Free consent' is a cognate term in the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, adopted in 1966 by the United Nations, and intended to be in force by 23 March 1976.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Article 7 of the covenant prohibits experiments conducted without the "free consent to medical or scientific experimentation" of the subject.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] As of September 2019, the covenant has 173 parties and six more signatories without ratification.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Informed consent can be complex to evaluate, because neither expressions of consent, nor expressions of understanding of implications, necessarily mean that full adult consent was in fact given, nor that full comprehension of relevant issues is internally digested.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Consent may be implied within the usual subtleties of human communication, rather than explicitly negotiated verbally or in writing.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] For example, if a doctor asks a patient to take their blood pressure, a patient may demonstrate consent by offering their arm for a blood pressure cuff.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In some cases consent cannot legally be possible, even if the person protests he does indeed understand and wish.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] There are also structured instruments for evaluating capacity to give informed consent, although no ideal instrument presently exists.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Thus, there is always a degree to which informed consent must be assumed or inferred based upon observation, or knowledge, or legal reliance.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This especially is the case in sexual or relational issues.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In medical or formal circumstances, explicit agreement by means of signature—normally relied on legally—regardless of actual consent, is the norm.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This is the case with certain procedures, such as a "do not resuscitate" directive that a patient signed before onset of their illness.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] A person may claim to understand the implications of some action, as part of consent, but in fact has failed to appreciate the possible consequences fully and may later deny the validity of the consent for this reason.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] A person signs a legal release form for a medical procedure, and later feels he did not really consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Unless he can show actual misinformation, the release is usually persuasive or conclusive in law, in that the clinician may rely legally upon it for consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] *In formal circumstances, a written consent usually legally overrides later denial of informed consent (unless obtained by misrepresentation)*.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Informed consent in the U.S. can be overridden in emergency medical situations pursuant to 21CFR50.24, which was first brought to the general public's attention via the controversy surrounding the study of Polyheme.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] For an individual to give valid informed consent, three components must be present: disclosure, capacity and voluntariness.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] An often-overlooked aspect of valid informed consent is the patient's understanding of terminology and outcomes.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The physician must explain the procedure, benefits, risks, and alternatives in words the patient can understand, as well as ensure that the patient does understand the information being relayed.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The process of explanation is meant to ensure the patient has considered the options carefully and grasps the possible risks associated without feeling pressured or rushed to agree to the procedure.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Exceptions to the typical consent process are only made during severe emergencies.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] As children often lack the decision-making ability or legal power (competence) to provide true informed consent for medical decisions, it often falls on parents or legal guardians to provide *informed permission* for medical decisions.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This "consent by proxy" usually works reasonably well, but can lead to ethical dilemmas when the judgment of the parents or guardians and the medical professional differ with regard to what constitutes appropriate decisions "in the best interest of the child".
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The American Academy of Pediatrics encourages medical professionals also to seek the assent of older children and adolescents by providing age appropriate information to these children to help empower them in the decision-making process.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Research on children has benefited society in many ways.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The only effective way to establish normal patterns of growth and metabolism is to do research on infants and young children.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] When addressing the issue of informed consent with children, the primary response is parental consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This is valid, although only legal guardians are able to consent for a child, not adult siblings.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Additionally, parents may not order the termination of a treatment that is required to keep a child alive, even if they feel it is in the best interest.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Guardians are typically involved in the consent of children, however a number of doctrines have developed that allow children to receive health treatments without parental consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] For example, emancipated minors may consent to medical treatment, and minors can also consent in an emergency.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Information provided to parents/guardians, and to children themselves, as part of clinical research is often written in ways that make them difficult to understand.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Waiver of the consent requirement may be applied in certain circumstances where no foreseeable harm is expected to result from the study or when permitted by law, federal regulations, or if an ethical review committee has approved the non-disclosure of certain information.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Besides studies with minimal risk, waivers of consent may be obtained in a military setting.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] 3. be carried out under all laws and regulations (i.e., Emergency Research Consent Waiver) including those pertinent to the FDA.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] While informed consent is a basic right and should be carried out effectively, if a patient is incapacitated due to injury or illness, it is still important that patients benefit from emergency experimentation.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and the Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) joined to create federal guidelines to permit emergency research, without informed consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] However, they can only proceed with the research if they obtain a waiver of informed consent (WIC) or an emergency exception from informed consent (EFIC).
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Medical sociologists have studied informed consent as well as bioethics more generally.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Oonagh Corrigan, looking at informed consent for research in patients, argues that much of the conceptualization of informed consent comes from research ethics and bioethics with a focus on patient autonomy, and notes that this aligns with a neoliberal worldview.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Corrigan argues that a model based solely around individual decision making does not accurately describe the reality of consent because of social processes: a view that has started to be acknowledged in bioethics.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] She feels that the liberal principles of informed consent are often in opposition with autocratic medical practices such that norms values and systems of expertise often shape an individuals ability to apply choice.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Patients who agree to participate in trials often do so because they feel that the trial was suggested by a doctor as the best intervention.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Patients may find being asked to consent within a limited time frame a burdensome intrusion on their care when it arises because a patient has to deal with a new condition.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Patients involved in trials may not be fully aware of the alternative treatments, and an awareness that there is uncertainty in the best treatment can help make patients more aware of this.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The doctrine of informed consent relates to professional negligence and establishes a breach of the duty of care owed to the patient (see duty of care, breach of the duty, and respect for persons).
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The doctrine of informed consent also has significant implications for medical trials of medications, devices, or procedures.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Arguably, this is "sufficient consent" rather than "informed consent." The UK has since departed from the Bolam test for judging standards of informed consent, due to the landmark ruling in *Montgomery v Lanarkshire Health Board*.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This moves away from the concept of a reasonable physician and instead uses the standard of a reasonable patient, and what risks an individual would attach significance to.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Medicine in the United States, Australia, and Canada takes this patient-centric approach to "informed consent." Informed consent in these jurisdictions requires healthcare providers to disclose significant risks, as well as risks of particular importance to that patient.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This approach combines an objective (a hypothetical reasonable patient) and subjective (this particular patient) approach.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Optimal establishment of an informed consent requires adaptation to cultural or other individual factors of the patient.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The informed consent doctrine is generally implemented through good healthcare practice: pre-operation discussions with patients and the use of medical consent forms in hospitals.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] However, reliance on a signed form should not undermine the basis of the doctrine in giving the patient an opportunity to weigh and respond to the risk.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In one British case, a doctor performing routine surgery on a woman noticed that she had cancerous tissue in her womb.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] He took the initiative to remove the woman's womb; however, as she had not given informed consent for this operation, the doctor was judged by the General Medical Council to have acted negligently.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The council stated that the woman should have been informed of her condition, and allowed to make her own decision.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] To document that informed consent has been given for a procedure, healthcare organisations have traditionally used paper-based consent forms on which the procedure and its risks and benefits are noted, and is signed by both patient and clinician.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In a number of healthcare organisations consent forms are scanned and maintained in an electronic document store.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] One form of digital consent is dynamic consent, which invites participants to provide consent in a granular way, and makes it easier for them to withdraw consent if they wish.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Patient satisfaction in the context of novel forms of informed consent has been a topic in scientific research.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Visual and auditory components in video-assisted informed consent and digital informed consent have proved to lead to higher patient satisfaction.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Integrating patients into treatment decisions (shared decision-making) and increasing transparency leads to better overall treatment adherence.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Electronic consent methods have been used to support indexing and retrieval of consent data, thus enhancing the ability to honor to patient intent and identify willing research participants.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] More recently, Health Sciences South Carolina, a statewide research collaborative focused on transforming healthcare quality, health information systems and patient outcomes, developed an open-source system called Research Permissions Management System (RPMS).
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The ability to give informed consent is governed by a general requirement of competency.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In common law jurisdictions, adults are presumed competent to consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This presumption can be rebutted, for instance, in circumstances of mental illness or other incompetence.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This may be prescribed in legislation or based on a common-law standard of inability to understand the nature of the procedure.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In cases of incompetent adults, a health care proxy makes medical decisions.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In the absence of a proxy, the medical practitioner is expected to act in the patient's best interests until a proxy can be found.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] By contrast, 'minors' (which may be defined differently in different jurisdictions) are generally presumed incompetent to consent, but depending on their age and other factors may be required to provide Informed assent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In some jurisdictions (e.g. much of the U.S.), this is a strict standard.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] England, Australia, Canada), this presumption may be rebutted through proof that the minor is 'mature' (the 'Gillick standard').
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In cases of incompetent minors, informed consent is usually required from the parent (rather than the 'best interests standard') although a parens patriae order may apply, allowing the court to dispense with parental consent in cases of refusal.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Research involving deception is controversial given the requirement for informed consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Deception typically arises in social psychology, when researching a particular psychological process requires that investigators deceive subjects.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] For example, in the Milgram experiment, researchers wanted to determine the willingness of participants to obey authority figures despite their personal conscientious objections.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] They had authority figures demand that participants deliver what they thought was an electric shock to another research participant.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] For the study to succeed, it was necessary to deceive the participants so they believed that the subject was a peer and that their electric shocks caused the peer actual pain.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Nonetheless, research involving deception prevents subjects from exercising their basic right of autonomous informed decision-making and conflicts with the ethical principle of respect for persons.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Moreover, the research should bear no potential harm to the subject as an outcome of deception, either physical pain or emotional distress.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Finally, the code requires a debriefing session in which the experimenter both tells the subject about the deception and gives subject the option of withdrawing the data.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Germany) require that the information giver be properly certified to make sure that no abortion is carried out for the financial gain of the abortion provider and to ensure that the decision to have an abortion is not swayed by any form of incentive.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Informed consent is part of ethical clinical research as well, in which a human subject voluntarily confirms his or her willingness to participate in a particular clinical trial, after having been informed of all aspects of the trial that are relevant to the subject's decision to participate.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This includes information about potential harms as well as potential benefits of clinical trial treatments.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Informed consent is documented by means of a written, signed, and dated informed consent form.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In medical research, the Nuremberg Code set a base international standard in 1947, in response to the ethical violation in the Holocaust.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Nowadays, medical research is overseen by an ethics committee that also oversees the informed consent process.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Research involving persons with disorders of consciousness presents additional consent challenges because potential participants often have absent, limited, or fluctuating decision-making capacity, requiring reliance on surrogate decision-makers.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] As the medical guidelines established in the Nuremberg Code were imported into the ethical guidelines for the social sciences, informed consent became a common part of the research procedure.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] However, while informed consent is the default in medical settings, it is not always required in the social sciences.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Here, firstly, research often involves low or no risk for participants, unlike in many medical experiments.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This may be done after the researcher(s) and an Ethics Committee and/or Institutional Review Board (IRB) weigh the risk to study participants against the benefits to society and whether participants participate voluntarily and are to be treated fairly.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The birth of new online media, such as social media, has complicated the idea of informed consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In an online environment people pay little attention to Terms of Use agreements and can subject themselves to research without thorough knowledge.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This issue came to the public light following a study conducted by Facebook in 2014, and published by that company and Cornell University.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Facebook conducted a study without consulting an Ethics Committee or IRB where they altered the Facebook News Feeds of roughly 700,000 users to reduce either the amount of positive or negative posts they saw for a week.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The study then analyzed if the users' status updates changed during the different conditions.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The study was published in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The lack of informed consent led to outrage among many researchers and users.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Many believed that by potentially altering the mood of users by altering what posts they see, Facebook put at-risk individuals at higher dangers for depression and suicide.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] However, supporters of Facebook claim that Facebook details that they have the right to use information for research in their terms of use.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Others say the experiment is just a part of Facebook's current work, which alters News Feeds algorithms continually to keep people interested and coming back to the site.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Others pointed out that this specific study is not unique but rather news organizations constantly try out different headlines using algorithms to elicit emotions and garner clicks or Facebook shares.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] They say this Facebook study is no different from things people already accept.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Still, others say that Facebook broke the law when conducting the experiment on users that did not give informed consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The Facebook study controversy raises numerous questions about informed consent and the differences in the ethical review process between publicly and privately funded research.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Some say Facebook was within its limits and others see the need for more informed consent and/or the establishment of in-house private review boards.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Some researchers and ethicists advocate for researchers to share experimental results with their subjects in a way they can understand, both as an ethical obligation and as a way to encourage more participation.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In 2023, the government of the United Kingdom proposed making this a requirement.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The Ethical, Legal, and Social Implications research program of the National Human Genome Research Institute in the United States has provided some funding for researchers to do this.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Other, long-standing controversies underscore the role for conflicts of interest among medical school faculty and researchers.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] For example, in 2014 coverage of University of California (UC) medical school faculty members has included news of ongoing corporate payments to researchers and practitioners from companies that market and produce the very devices and treatments they recommend to patients.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Robert Pedowitz, the former chairman of UCLA's orthopedic surgery department, reported concern that his colleague's financial conflicts of interest could negatively affect patient care or research into new treatments.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In a subsequent lawsuit about whistleblower retaliation, the university provided a $10 million settlement to Pedowitz while acknowledging no wrongdoing.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The patient has multiple choices and is not compelled to choose a particular one.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] These practices are part of what constitutes informed consent, and their history is the history of informed consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] They combine to form the modern concept of informed consent—which rose in response to particular incidents in modern research.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Whereas various cultures in various places practiced informed consent, the modern concept of informed consent was developed by people who drew influence from Western tradition.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Historians cite a series of medical guidelines to trace the history of informed consent in medical practice.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The Hippocratic Oath, a Greek text dating to 500 B.C.E., was the first set of Western writings giving guidelines for the conduct of medical professionals.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Consent by patients as well as several other, now considered fundamental issues, is not mentioned.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The Hippocratic Corpus advises that physicians conceal most information from patients to give the patients the best care.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The rationale is a beneficence model for care—the doctor knows better than the patient, and therefore should direct the patient's care, because the patient is not likely to have better ideas than the doctor.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Henri de Mondeville, a French surgeon who in the 14th century, wrote about medical practice.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] He traced his ideas to the Hippocratic Oath.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Among his recommendations were that doctors "promise a cure to every patient" in hopes that the good prognosis would inspire a good outcome to treatment.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Mondeville never mentioned getting consent, but did emphasize the need for the patient to have confidence in the doctor.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] He also advised that when deciding therapeutically unimportant details the doctor should meet the patients' requests "so far as they do not interfere with treatment".
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In Ottoman Empire records there exists an agreement from 1539 in which negotiates details of a surgery, including fee and a commitment not to sue in case of death.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This is the oldest identified written document in which a patient acknowledges risk of medical treatment and writes to express their willingness to proceed.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Benjamin Rush was an 18th-century United States physician who was influenced by the Age of Enlightenment cultural movement.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Because of this, he advised that doctors ought to share as much information as possible with patients.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] He recommended that doctors educate the public and respect a patient's informed decision to accept therapy.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] There is no evidence that he supported seeking a consent from patients.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In a lecture titled "On the duties of patients to their physicians", he stated that patients should be strictly obedient to the physician's orders; this was representative of much of his writings.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] John Gregory, Rush's teacher, wrote similar views that a doctor could best practice beneficence by making decisions for the patients without their consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Thomas Percival was a British physician who published a book called *Medical Ethics* in 1803.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Percival was a student of the works of Gregory and various earlier Hippocratic physicians.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Like all previous works, Percival's *Medical Ethics* makes no mention of soliciting for the consent of patients or respecting their decisions.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Percival said that patients have a right to truth, but when the physician could provide better treatment by lying or withholding information, he advised that the physician do as he thought best.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] When the American Medical Association was founded they in 1847 produced a work called the first edition of the *American Medical Association Code of Medical Ethics*.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Many sections of this book are verbatim copies of passages from Percival's *Medical Ethics*.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] A new concept in this book was the idea that physicians should fully disclose all patient details truthfully when talking to other physicians, but the text does not also apply this idea to disclosing information to patients.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Through this text, Percival's ideas became pervasive guidelines throughout the United States as other texts were derived from them.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Worthington Hooker was an American physician who in 1849 published *Physician and Patient*.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This medical ethics book was radical demonstrating understanding of the AMA's guidelines and Percival's philosophy and soundly rejecting all directives that a doctor should lie to patients.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In Hooker's view, benevolent deception is not fair to the patient, and he lectured widely on this topic.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Hooker's ideas were not broadly influential.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The principle of informed consent was not legally binding until first recorded in the *Salgo v.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Leland Stanford Jr University Board of Trustees* case of 1957.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This case was one of the first to draw attention to the need for patients to understand the risks and benefits of their procedures, since at that time a lack of informed consent was not considered negligence.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Spence* case in 1972 officially established the principle of informed consent in US law.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Canterbury underwent a laminectomy to relieve back pain but was not informed of the risk of paralysis.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] While left by himself, he fell off his bed and was later paralyzed from the waist down; he required further surgeries but was never completely relieved of paralysis in his bowels and bladder.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Earlier legal cases had created the underpinnings for informed consent, but his judgment gave a detailed and thought through discourse on the matter.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The judgment cites cases going back to 1914 as precedent for informed consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Historians cite a series of human subject research experiments to trace the history of informed consent in research.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Army Yellow Fever Commission "is considered the first research group in history to use consent forms." In 1900, Major Walter Reed was appointed head of the four man U.S.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Army Yellow Fever Commission in Cuba that determined mosquitoes were the vector for yellow fever transmission.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] His earliest experiments were probably done without formal documentation of informed consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In later experiments he obtained support from appropriate military and administrative authorities.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] He then drafted what is now "one of the oldest series of extant informed consent documents." The three surviving examples are in Spanish with English translations; two have an individual's signature and one is marked with an X.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] On January 29, 1951, shortly after the birth of her son Joseph, Henrietta Lacks entered Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore with profuse bleeding.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] She was diagnosed with aggressive cervical cancer and was treated with inserts of radium tubes.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] During her radiation treatments for the tumor, two samples—one of healthy cells, the other of malignant cells—were removed from her cervix without her knowledge or permission.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] There is no evidence that the doctor checked the cells for other conditions before passing them on for research.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Later that year, 31-year-old Henrietta Lacks died from the cancer.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Her cells were capable of surviving and dividing indefinitely when cultured, creating HeLa cells, but the family, which was living in poverty, was not informed until 1973; the family learned the truth when scientists asked for DNA samples after finding that HeLa had contaminated other samples.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In 2013, researchers published the genome without the Lacks family's consent.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] As a result of this incident, pushes were made for major changes in the US's process for informed consent in biospecimen research.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The Milgram experiment is the name of a 1961 experiment conducted by American psychologist Stanley Milgram.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In the experiment Milgram had an authority figure order research participants to commit a disturbing act of harming another person.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] After the experiment he would reveal that he had deceived the participants and that they had not hurt anyone, but the research participants were upset at the experience of having participated in the research.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] The experiment raised broad discussion on the ethics of recruiting participants for research without giving them full information about the nature of the research.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Southam used HeLa cells to inject into cancer patients and Ohio State Penitentiary inmates without informed consent to determine if people could become immune to cancer and if cancer could be transmitted.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] With the growth of bioethics in the 21st century to include environmental sustainability, some authors, such as Cristina Richie have proposed a "green consent".
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] This would include information and education about the climate impact of pharmaceuticals (carbon cost of medications) and climate change health hazards.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Artificial intelligence (AI) became widespread in the 21st century.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] It raises many ethical concerns in the medical field, such as the patients’ awareness that they may be interacting with an AI system, as it is being gradually integrated into scanning, surgery, and diagnoses.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] A number of companies, inspired by the ChatGPT3 system that was released in December 2022, developed AI therapists, which are mental health chatbots that can provide treatment information and perform mental health therapy.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Patients must be educated about AI usage to promote trust in the systems.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Privacy Rule establishes a framework for patient authorization that is distinct from but related to informed consent for treatment.
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] Under the Privacy Rule, covered entities generally may not use or disclose protected health information without a valid written authorization from the individual, except for purposes of treatment, payment, and health care operations or where otherwise permitted by the rule (45 CFR 164.508).
[src:consent-management/informed-consent] A valid HIPAA authorization must contain specific elements including a description of the information to be disclosed, the purpose of the disclosure, an expiration date, and the individual's right to revoke the authorization.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In the case of a business, it is often a statement that declares a party's policy on how it collects, stores, and releases personal information it collects.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] It informs the client what specific information is collected, and whether it is kept confidential, shared with partners, or sold to other firms or enterprises.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Privacy policies typically represent a broader, more generalized treatment, as opposed to data use statements, which tend to be more detailed and specific.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The exact contents of a privacy policy will depend upon the applicable law and may need to address requirements across geographical boundaries and legal jurisdictions.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Most countries have their own legislation and guidelines of who is covered, what information can be collected, and what it can be used for.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In general, data protection laws in Europe cover the private sector as well as the public sector.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Their privacy laws apply not only to government operations but also to private enterprises and commercial transactions.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 1968, the Council of Europe began to study the effects of technology on human rights, recognizing the new threats posed by computer technology that could link and transmit in ways not widely available before.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 1969 the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) began to examine the implications of personal information leaving the country.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] All this led the council to recommend that policy be developed to protect personal data held by both the private and public sectors, leading to Convention 108.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 1981, Convention for the Protection of Individuals with regard to Automatic Processing of Personal Data (Convention 108) was introduced.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] One of the first privacy laws ever enacted was the Swedish Data Act in 1973, followed by the West German Data Protection Act in 1977 and the French Law on Informatics, Data Banks and Freedoms in 1978.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In the United States, concern over privacy policy starting around the late 1960s and 1970s led to the passage of the Fair Credit Reporting Act.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Although this act was not designed to be a privacy law, the act gave consumers the opportunity to examine their credit files and correct errors.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] It also placed restrictions on the use of information in credit records.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Several congressional study groups in the late 1960s examined the growing ease with which automated personal information could be gathered and matched with other information.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] One such group was an advisory committee of the United States Department of Health and Human Services, which in 1973 drafted a code of principles called the Fair Information Practices.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The work of the advisory committee led to the Privacy Act in 1974.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The United States signed the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development guidelines in 1980.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In Canada, a Privacy Commissioner of Canada was established under the Canadian Human Rights Act in 1977.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 1982, the appointment of a Privacy Commissioner was part of the new Privacy Act.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Canada signed the OECD guidelines in 1984.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] There are significant differences between the EU data protection and US data privacy laws.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] These standards must be met not only by businesses operating in the EU but also by any organization that transfers personal information collected concerning citizens of the EU.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 2001 the United States Department of Commerce worked to ensure legal compliance for US organizations under an opt-in Safe Harbor Program.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The FTC has approved eTRUST to certify streamlined compliance with the US-EU Safe Harbor.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 1995 the European Union (EU) introduced the Data Protection Directive for its member states.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] As a result, many organizations doing business within the EU began to draft policies to comply with this Directive.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Federal Trade Commission (FTC) published the Fair Information Principles which provided a set of non-binding governing principles for the commercial use of personal information.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] While not mandating policy, these principles provided guidance of the developing concerns of how to draft privacy policies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The United States does not have a specific federal regulation establishing universal implementation of privacy policies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Congress has, at times, considered comprehensive laws regulating the collection of information online, such as the Consumer Internet Privacy Enhancement Act and the Online Privacy Protection Act of 2001, but none have been enacted.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 2001, the FTC stated an express preference for "more law enforcement, not more laws" and promoted continued focus on industry self-regulation.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In many cases, the FTC enforces the terms of privacy policies as promises made to consumers using the authority granted by Section 5 of the FTC Act which prohibits unfair or deceptive marketing practices.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The FTC's powers are statutorily restricted in some cases; for example, airlines are subject to the authority of the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA), and cell phone carriers are subject to the authority of the Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In some cases, private parties enforce the terms of privacy policies by filing class action lawsuits, which may result in settlements or judgments.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] However, such lawsuits are often not an option, due to arbitration clauses in the privacy policies or other terms of service agreements.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Some states have implemented more stringent regulations for privacy policies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The California *Online Privacy Protection Act of 2003 – Business and Professions Code sections 22575-22579* requires "any commercial websites or online services that collect personal information on California residents through a web site to conspicuously post a privacy policy on the site".
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Both Nebraska and Pennsylvania have laws treating misleading statements in privacy policies published on websites as deceptive or fraudulent business practices.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Canada's federal Privacy Law applicable to the private sector is formally referred to as Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA).
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The purpose of the act is to establish rules to govern the collection, use, and disclosure of personal information by commercial organizations.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The organization is allowed to collect, disclose and use the amount of information for the purposes that a reasonable person would consider appropriate in the circumstance.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The Act establishes the Privacy Commissioner of Canada as the Ombudsman for addressing any complaints that are filed against organizations.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The Commissioner works to resolve problems through voluntary compliance, rather than heavy-handed enforcement.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The Commissioner investigates complaints, conducts audits, promotes awareness of and undertakes research about privacy matters.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The right to privacy is a highly developed area of law in Europe.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] All the member states of the European Union (EU) are also signatories of the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR).
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Article 8 of the ECHR provides a right to respect for one's "private and family life, his home and his correspondence", subject to certain restrictions.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The European Court of Human Rights has given this article a very broad interpretation in its jurisprudence.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 1980, in an effort to create a comprehensive data protection system throughout Europe, the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) issued its "Recommendations of the Council Concerning Guidelines Governing the Protection of Privacy and Trans-Border Flows of Personal Data".
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Accountability—data subjects should have a method available to them to hold data collectors accountable for not following the above principles.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The OECD guidelines, however, were nonbinding, and data privacy laws still varied widely across Europe.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The US, while endorsing the OECD’s recommendations, did nothing to implement them within the United States.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] However, all seven principles were incorporated into the EU Directive.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 1995, the EU adopted the Data Protection Directive, which regulates the processing of personal data within the EU.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] There were significant differences between the EU data protection and equivalent U.S. data privacy laws.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] These standards must be met not only by businesses operating in the EU but also by any organization that transfers personal information collected concerning a citizen of the EU.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The FTC has approved a number of US providers to certify compliance with the US-EU Safe Harbor.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Since 2010 Safe Harbor is criticised, especially by German publicly appointed privacy protectors, because the FTC's will to assert the defined rules had not been implemented in a proper manner even after revealing disharmonies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] From 25 May 2018, the Data Protection Directive was superseded by the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which harmonizes privacy rules across all EU member states.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Data controllers must also provide the opportunity for their data to be made portable in a common format, and for it to be erased under certain circumstances.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The Privacy Act 1988 provides the legal framework for privacy in Australia.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] It includes a number of national privacy principles.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] There are thirteen privacy principles under the Privacy Act.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] It oversees and regulates the collection, use and disclosure of people's private information, makes sure who is responsible if there is a violation, and the rights of individuals to access their information.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The Information Technology (Amendment) Act, 2008 made significant changes to the Information Technology Act, 2000, introducing Section 43A.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] This section provides compensation in the case where a corporate body is negligent in implementing and maintaining reasonable security practices and procedures and thereby causes wrongful loss or wrongful gain to any person.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] This applies when a corporate body possesses, deals or handles any sensitive personal data or information in a computer resource that it owns, controls or operates.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In 2011, the Government of India prescribed the Information Technology (Reasonable security practices and procedures and sensitive personal data or information) Rules, 2011 by publishing it in the Official Gazette.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] These rules require a body corporate to provide a privacy policy for handling of or dealing in personal information including sensitive personal data or information.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Reasonable security practices and procedures.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The privacy policy should be published on the website of the body corporate, and be made available for view by providers of information who have provided personal information under lawful contract.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Online certification or "seal" programs are an example of industry self-regulation of privacy policies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Seal programs usually require implementation of fair information practices as determined by the certification program and may require continued compliance monitoring.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] TRUSTArc (formerly TRUSTe), the first online privacy seal program, included more than 1,800 members by 2007.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Other online seal programs include the Trust Guard Privacy Verified program, eTrust, and Webtrust.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Some websites also define their privacy policies using P3P or Internet Content Rating Association (ICRA), allowing browsers to automatically assess the level of privacy offered by the site, and allowing access only when the site's privacy practices are in line with the user's privacy settings.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] However, these technical solutions do not guarantee websites actually follows the claimed privacy policies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] These implementations also require users to configure their own browser privacy settings or accept a recommended set of settings.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] These automated privacy policies have not been popular either with websites or their users.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] To reduce the burden of interpreting individual privacy policies, re-usable, certified policies available from a policy server have been proposed by Jøsang, Fritsch and Mahler.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Many critics have attacked the efficacy and legitimacy of privacy policies found on the Internet.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Concerns exist about the effectiveness of industry-regulated privacy policies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] For example, a 2000 FTC report Privacy Online: Fair Information Practices in the Electronic Marketplace found that while the vast majority of websites surveyed had some manner of privacy disclosure, most did not meet the standard set in the FTC Principles.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In addition, many organizations reserve the express right to unilaterally change the terms of their policies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] In June 2009 the EFF website TOSback began tracking such changes on 56 popular internet services, including monitoring the privacy policies of Amazon, Google and Facebook.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] There are also questions about whether consumers understand privacy policies and whether they help consumers make more informed decisions.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] A 2002 report from the Stanford Persuasive Technology Lab contended that a website's visual designs had more influence than the website's privacy policy when consumers assessed the website's credibility.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] A 2007 study by Carnegie Mellon University claimed "when not presented with prominent privacy information..." consumers were "…likely to make purchases from the vendor with the lowest price, regardless of that site's privacy policies".
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] However, the same study also showed that when information about privacy practices is clearly presented, consumers prefer retailers who better protect their privacy and some are willing to "pay a premium to purchase from more privacy protective websites".
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Furthermore, a 2007 study at the University of California, Berkeley found that "75% of consumers think as long as a site has a privacy policy it means it won't share data with third parties," confusing the existence of a privacy policy with extensive privacy protection.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Based on the common nature of this misunderstanding, researcher Joseph Turow argued to the U.S.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Federal Trade Commission that the term "privacy policy" thus constitutes a deceptive trade practice and that alternative phrasing like "how we use your information" should be used instead.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Privacy policies suffer generally from a lack of precision, especially when compared with the emerging form of the Data Use Statement.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Where privacy statements provide a more general overview of data collection and use, data use statements represent a much more specific treatment.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] As a result, privacy policies may not meet the increased demand for transparency that data use statements provide.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] Critics also question if consumers even read privacy policies or can understand what they read.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] A 2001 study by the Privacy Leadership Initiative claimed only 3% of consumers read privacy policies carefully, and 64% briefly glanced at, or never read privacy policies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The average website user once having read a privacy statement may have more uncertainty about the trustworthiness of the website than before.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] One possible issue is length and complexity of policies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] According to a 2008 Carnegie Mellon study, the average length of a privacy policy is 2,500 words and requires an average of 10 minutes to read.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] The study cited that "Privacy policies are hard to read" and, as a result, "read infrequently".
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] However, any efforts to make the information more presentable simplify the information to the point that it does not convey the extent to which users' data is being shared and sold.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] This is known as the "transparency paradox".
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] There have been many studies carried out by researchers to evaluate the privacy policies of the websites of companies.
[src:consent-management/privacy-policy] One study uses natural language processing and deep learning as a proposed solution to automatically assess the efficiency of companies' privacy policies, in order to help the users become more aware.
